{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RAA4hCaWjSMSB8rFUTZxWP","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Workflows\n     2→\n     3→Cloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4→\n     5→## Workflow Locations\n     6→\n     7→Cloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8→\n     9→**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) — Run inside a Docker\n    10→container via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11→standard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12→\n    13→**Host workflow** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) — Runs on the host machine as the daemon\n    14→process. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15→dispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16→point for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17→\n    18→The convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    19→file is a parse error.\n    20→\n    21→## Concepts\n    22→\n    23→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    24→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    25→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    26→| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    27→| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    28→| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step                              |\n    29→| done     | Built-in terminal step — successful completion                     |\n    30→| abort    | Built-in terminal step — failure with error reporting              |\n    31→\n    32→## Step Types\n    33→\n    34→Step type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    35→\n    36→**agent** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    37→to the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    38→container. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    39→\n    40→**script** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    41→any deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    42→\n    43→**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) — Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    44→until it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    45→\n    46→A step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    47→parse error.\n    48→\n    49→## DSL Syntax\n    50→\n    51→```\n    52→workflow \"implement-feature\" {\n    53→  step code {\n    54→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    55→    container {\n    56→      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n    57→      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    58→    }\n    59→    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n    60→  }\n    61→\n    62→  step check {\n    63→    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    64→    results = [pass, fail]\n    65→  }\n    66→\n    67→  step review {\n    68→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    69→    input = step.code.output\n    70→    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n    71→  }\n    72→\n    73→  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step\n    74→  code:success -> check\n    75→  code:fail -> abort\n    76→  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n    77→\n    78→  check:pass -> review\n    79→  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n    80→\n    81→  review:approved -> done\n    82→  review:changes_requested -> code\n    83→}\n    84→```\n    85→\n    86→## Key Properties\n    87→\n    88→**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n    89→field makes it a script step.\n    90→\n    91→**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n    92→report. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n    93→\n    94→**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n    95→existing ones by rewiring — without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n    96→Cloche's self-evolution feature.\n    97→\n    98→**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n    99→wired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   100→\n   101→## Host Workflow Example\n   102→\n   103→```\n   104→# .cloche/host.cloche — runs on the host machine\n   105→workflow \"main\" {\n   106→  step prepare-prompt {\n   107→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   108→    results = [success, fail]\n   109→  }\n   110→\n   111→  step develop {\n   112→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   113→    prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n   114→    results       = [success, fail]\n   115→  }\n   116→\n   117→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   118→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   119→  develop:success        -> done\n   120→  develop:fail           -> done\n   121→}\n   122→```\n   123→\n   124→The `workflow_name` step reads the prompt from the previous step's output (or\n   125→`prompt_step` override), dispatches a container workflow run, and blocks until it\n   126→completes.\n   127→\n   128→## Execution Model\n   129→\n   130→**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   131→container. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   132→wiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   133→All steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   134→\n   135→**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. Script\n   136→steps run via `sh -c`, and workflow steps dispatch container runs via the daemon's\n   137→standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`,\n   138→etc.) are injected into each step.\n   139→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01JP4KapEteMPEP4aikpsVjB","session_id":"4fdefc21-58a5-4b42-a6f6-efcac5882b09","uuid":"94be2604-a519-480a-9c54-03817924b688"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VkDXyxPAxwf5oKAuEad9Ek","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# CLOCHE\n     2→\n     3→A system for grow-coding high quality applications.\n     4→\n     5→# What is it\n     6→\n     7→Cloche provides \n     8→- containerized environments for coding agents to operate in isolation\n     9→- a workflow syntax for linking Agentic and Script-driven task nodes\n    10→- a focus on creating validated code\n    11→- self-evolving tooling that grows with your codebase in response to encountered errors\n    12→\n    13→## Installation\n    14→\n    15→See [docs/INSTALL.md](docs/INSTALL.md) for full installation instructions\n    16→covering build from source, `go install`, and other methods.\n    17→\n    18→## Containers\n    19→\n    20→Coding agents are powerful, but running them interactively turns the human into the bottleneck.\n    21→\n    22→On the otherhand, running them in \"yolo\" mode is wildly risky.\n    23→\n    24→To allow our agents to run in a balance of safety and speed, we must disrupt the Lethal Trifecta.\n    25→\n    26→Firstly, we remove their access to the full filesystem - the docker containers have access only to their\n    27→own filespace - only copies are used - no file mounts. Environment variables are only those provided by the host\n    28→to the container. \n    29→\n    30→Second, network access is limited to allowlists to ensure your agents can have e.g. free access to library documentation or your\n    31→internal documentation, but not the internet at large!\n    32→\n    33→\n    34→## Workflows\n    35→\n    36→see our [Workflows](docs/workflows.md) documentation!\n    37→\n    38→## Validated code\n    39→\n    40→Your agents are fast, but that speed shouldn't come at the cost of quality.\n    41→\n    42→Keep your validation checks in the loop with your coding agent - go beyond unit tests!\n    43→- validate complexity measurements\n    44→- automated code review\n    45→- auto-split large commits into stacked branches, individually reviewed and validated to keep commits simple and clean\n    46→- custom script and agent support to add your own checks to the mix\n    47→- failures are tracked and classified for use in autogenerating future validation checks\n    48→- validation failure feedback triggers retries to automatically resolve issues before they reach CI\n    49→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01JP4KapEteMPEP4aikpsVjB","session_id":"4fdefc21-58a5-4b42-a6f6-efcac5882b09","uuid":"c77cadb4-0ebd-4219-b9df-5de384b67e82"}
